and Ms. Against Abortion...


1161
01:11:10.480 --> 01:11:14.107
Jack, I spent the holidays flying
back and forth across this country


1162
01:11:14.275 --> 01:11:15.442
and I'm worried.

1163
01:11:15.777 --> 01:11:18.987
The place seems all out of focus,
sea to shining sea.


1164
01:11:19.739 --> 01:11:22.365
We've both flown many times, Shana,
coast to coast.


1165
01:11:22.533 --> 01:11:23.867
But we see a different land below.

1166
01:11:24.035 --> 01:11:26.745
And you have them argue
and that's punditry.


1167
01:11:27.121 --> 01:11:28.538
That's enlightenment.

1168
01:11:28.664 --> 01:11:31.333
Dan, there's an old saying:
"Behind every successful man


1169
01:11:31.542 --> 01:11:34.336
there's a woman,
a loving, giving, caring woman."


1170
01:11:36.631 --> 01:11:38.048
Jane, you ignorant slut.

1171
01:11:42.178 --> 01:11:44.971
Argument is sugar
and the rest of us are flies.


1172
01:11:48.142 --> 01:11:49.559
Welcome to Radio 81.

1173
01:11:49.852 --> 01:11:51.978
I think this is Ron
and Gore Vidal is also here.


1174
01:11:52.146 --> 01:11:54.689
I invariably agree
with your social views,


1175
01:11:55.066 --> 01:11:56.566
the content of your ideas.

1176
01:11:56.984 --> 01:11:59.361
And I contest with Buckley's views.

1177
01:11:59.821 --> 01:12:03.198
But I hear you talk,
and William Buckley talk,


1178
01:12:03.491 --> 01:12:06.618
I feel that Buckley
is the more honest man.


1179
01:12:07.161 --> 01:12:09.663
In what way do you find him
more honest than I?


1180
01:12:09.831 --> 01:12:13.041
I think it goes way back
to the debates


1181
01:12:13.209 --> 01:12:15.168
you had with him on television.

1182
01:12:15.461 --> 01:12:18.088
And you literally blew his mind.

1183
01:12:18.256 --> 01:12:20.298
I've never seen Buckley
lose it like that.


1184
01:12:20.466 --> 01:12:22.467
He swore at you
and stood up and said,


1185
01:12:22.635 --> 01:12:24.511
"How dare you call me a neo
-Nazi!"

1186
01:12:24.679 --> 01:12:27.097
I thought him the scum of the world,
you see.


1187
01:12:27.265 --> 01:12:28.890
- I know, he was over-excited, yeah?
- Yes.


1188
01:12:29.058 --> 01:12:30.851
- But I think--
- What did you find dishonest


1189
01:12:31.018 --> 01:12:32.602
about my performance?

1190
01:12:32.812 --> 01:12:35.647
It had to do with
the glee in your face,


1191
01:12:35.815 --> 01:12:37.607
in your eyes,
that you could not hide.


1192
01:12:37.775 --> 01:12:40.318
Well, that isn't...
I wasn't being dishonest.


1193
01:12:40.570 --> 01:12:42.737
I am a happy warrior.

1194
01:12:42.905 --> 01:12:44.573
I'm in battle, 
I'm enjoying it.

1195
01:12:44.740 --> 01:12:46.783
This is what these things are about.

1196
01:12:46.951 --> 01:12:49.161
If somebody that I regard
is a very bad person...


1197
01:12:50.079 --> 01:12:53.915
politically, then to expose him
on television for what he is


1198
01:12:54.083 --> 01:12:55.667
is my job.

1199
01:12:56.043 --> 01:12:58.670
And I think I accomplished it
very nicely, so did he.


1200
01:12:58.880 --> 01:13:01.089
He brought suit against me
as a result of it.


1201
01:13:02.967 --> 01:13:06.386
A year after these debates,
in August of 1969,


1202
01:13:06.846 --> 01:13:09.931
Esquire published a long essay
that Bill had written,


1203
01:13:10.850 --> 01:13:12.559
something like 12,000 words

1204
01:13:13.227 --> 01:13:17.189
trying to explore why he had
reacted the way he did.


1205
01:13:18.900 --> 01:13:21.026
Buckley couldn't let it go.

1206
01:13:21.194 --> 01:13:23.111
He couldn't let this thing go.

1207
01:13:25.072 --> 01:13:28.241
He thought he would avenge himself
or explain himself


1208
01:13:28.409 --> 01:13:32.370
by writing in a sophisticated way
about Vidal in Esquire.


1209
01:13:35.583 --> 01:13:38.126
For days and weeks,
indeed for months,


1210
01:13:38.294 --> 01:13:41.004
I tormented myself
with the question...


1211
01:13:41.881 --> 01:13:43.965
"What should I have said?"

1212
01:13:44.759 --> 01:13:46.801
Was my mistake that of
going on TV at all,


1213
01:13:46.969 --> 01:13:49.012
in light of the abundant warnings,
with Vidal?


1214
01:13:50.556 --> 01:13:53.350
Could it be that my emotional
reaction was defensible


1215
01:13:53.517 --> 01:13:55.018
and even healthy,

1216
01:13:55.186 --> 01:13:57.938
but that my words were ill-chosen?

1217
01:13:58.314 --> 01:14:01.691
The problem was, instead of
putting a cap on the debate,


1218
01:14:01.859 --> 01:14:04.569
he's perpetuating it
on another platform,


1219
01:14:04.779 --> 01:14:06.112
which really made it worse.

1220
01:14:10.284 --> 01:14:12.494
Vidal then replied

1221
01:14:12.703 --> 01:14:18.208
in print to this barn burner piece
to take the stage back.


1222
01:14:21.754 --> 01:14:24.631
On Wednesday,
August 28, at 9:30,


1223
01:14:24.924 --> 01:14:27.634
in full view of ten million people,

1224
01:14:28.052 --> 01:14:31.763
the little door in William F. Buckley
Jr.'s forehead suddenly opened


1225
01:14:32.056 --> 01:14:36.101
and out sprang that wild cuckoo
which I had always known was there,


1226
01:14:36.269 --> 01:14:39.938
but had wanted so much for others,
preferably millions of others,


1227
01:14:40.106 --> 01:14:41.773
to get a good look at.

1228
01:14:43.067 --> 01:14:46.528
Vidal is always suspicious
of Buckley's sexuality.


1229
01:14:47.363 --> 01:14:51.283
And makes references
that suggest that


1230
01:14:51.450 --> 01:14:54.828
Buckley has an attraction
to the homoerotic.


1231
01:14:56.414 --> 01:14:58.581
There was always a question of...

1232
01:14:59.208 --> 01:15:00.250
Um...

1233
01:15:02.837 --> 01:15:04.212
I don't know how to put it.

1234
01:15:05.589 --> 01:15:09.175
That there was a kind of
sexual ambiguity about Bill.


1235
01:15:10.511 --> 01:15:12.470
There were rumors,
none of them substantiated.


1236
01:15:12.638 --> 01:15:14.931
It was more a manner of affect,
really.


1237
01:15:15.933 --> 01:15:18.268
Buckley was kind of an effete guy.

1238
01:15:18.853 --> 01:15:22.397
If you read the piece,
you are led to believe


1239
01:15:22.565 --> 01:15:27.694
that among other things, William F.
Buckley, Jr. was homosexual.


1240
01:15:31.991 --> 01:15:35.535
Buckley instituted a suit
against Esquire magazine


1241
01:15:35.703 --> 01:15:37.287
and against Vidal.

1242
01:15:38.039 --> 01:15:41.833
Vidal instituted a countersuit
against Buckley.


1243
01:15:42.335 --> 01:15:46.755
The litigation
went on for three years.


1244
01:15:46.922 --> 01:15:49.007
Is that still going back
and forth in the courts?


1245
01:15:49.467 --> 01:15:51.676
It's going more back than forth.

1246
01:15:51.844 --> 01:15:54.679
Just... it keeps on ticking away
like a bomb.


1247
01:15:55.473 --> 01:15:57.849
At the time, it was
one of the longest lawsuits


1248
01:15:58.017 --> 01:16:01.019
between two American public
intellectuals there'd ever been.


1249
01:16:01.187 --> 01:16:02.395
Neither of them ever tired of it.

1250
01:16:02.563 --> 01:16:05.940
It gave them enormous opportunity
for the practice of malice.


1251
01:16:06.525 --> 01:16:08.735
It's still litigious, is it?

1252
01:16:08.903 --> 01:16:10.278
Very litigious.

1253
01:16:12.198 --> 01:16:16.534
By the third year, Esquire
said, "We've had enough."


1254
01:16:18.412 --> 01:16:20.163
Esquire ended up settling.

1255
01:16:20.331 --> 01:16:23.166
And then Buckley,
in a stroke of brilliance,


1256
01:16:23.334 --> 01:16:25.752
gives a press conference
and declares victory.


1257
01:16:26.337 --> 01:16:29.506
In the public imagination,
people thought that he had won


1258
01:16:29.673 --> 01:16:32.550
this lawsuit they didn't
understand in the first place.


1259
01:16:32.843 --> 01:16:34.511
I know that Gore hated that.

1260
01:16:34.678 --> 01:16:37.806
Was it ever resolved, who came out
ahead on that whole thing?


1261
01:16:38.182 --> 01:16:40.809
Well, it sort of went on
for several years.


1262
01:16:40.976 --> 01:16:42.811
And then about a week
before we'd go into court,


1263
01:16:42.978 --> 01:16:44.479
he called off the suit.

1264
01:16:44.647 --> 01:16:46.898
- Pulled the suit out from under you?
- Exactly.


1265
01:16:47.066 --> 01:16:50.110
Exactly.
I was looking forward to that.


1266
01:16:59.787 --> 01:17:03.790
Why do you work so hard?
Why do you work so darn hard?


1267
01:17:04.208 --> 01:17:05.834
There's a lot to do.

1268
01:17:06.502 --> 01:17:09.421
Bill Buckley,
the popularizer, laid the foundation


1269
01:17:10.089 --> 01:17:11.673
for the conservative movement.

1270
01:17:11.841 --> 01:17:14.050
Which enabled Ronald Reagan
to come along


1271
01:17:14.218 --> 01:17:17.679
and to win that presidency
by the margin that he did.


1272
01:17:19.432 --> 01:17:22.308
I can't tell you exactly when
I discovered National Review.


1273
01:17:23.018 --> 01:17:25.186
It had a profound impact on me.

1274
01:17:28.732 --> 01:17:31.568
Well, my relationship
to Ronald Reagan was pretty close.


1275
01:17:32.570 --> 01:17:35.613
There was an affinity of ideas.

1276
01:17:38.033 --> 01:17:40.285
I visited him and he visited me.

1277
01:17:40.453 --> 01:17:42.954
We took a liking to each other.

1278
01:17:43.122 --> 01:17:44.539
Certainly I to him.

1279
01:17:46.208 --> 01:17:48.751
When Ronald Reagan
saluted William Buckley


1280
01:17:48.919 --> 01:17:51.004
and the National Review
as president,


1281
01:17:51.297 --> 01:17:52.672
Buckley became a king maker.

1282
01:17:52.840 --> 01:17:54.382
And he was seen
to be a king maker.

1283
01:17:54.550 --> 01:17:58.720
And appearance is at least as
important as reality in this world.


1284
01:18:00.014 --> 01:18:02.182
When Buckley
and Reagan were ascended,


1285
01:18:02.349 --> 01:18:06.978
and Vidal's political ideology
was taking a backseat,


1286
01:18:07.146 --> 01:18:09.397
I think this was actually
a great period for him.


1287
01:18:09.607 --> 01:18:12.192
Some of his greatest writing
occurred in the '80s,


1288
01:18:12.359 --> 01:18:14.277
both in essays and in literature.

1289
01:18:15.279 --> 01:18:16.988
When another right-wing critic

1290
01:18:17.156 --> 01:18:19.699
attacked Gore Vidal
as being anti-American,


1291
01:18:20.826 --> 01:18:22.911
Gore's reply was,
"How can you call me anti-American?


1292
01:18:23.078 --> 01:18:24.871
I'm the country's official
biographer."


1293
01:18:32.254 --> 01:18:34.923
In Burr,
Vidal got off one of his great lines.


1294
01:18:35.508 --> 01:18:39.761
It was the beginning of Vidal's
attempt at revenge on Buckley.


1295
01:18:40.429 --> 01:18:44.516
I believe his name was
"William de la Touche Clancey".


1296
01:18:45.267 --> 01:18:46.935
And I think Vidal said somewhere

1297
01:18:47.102 --> 01:18:49.812
that it could not possibly
be based on anyone,


1298
01:18:50.064 --> 01:18:53.233
meaning that of course
it's based on Bill.


1299
01:18:54.276 --> 01:18:56.611
William de la Touche
Clancey's voice


1300
01:18:56.779 --> 01:18:59.113
is like that of a furious goose,

1301
01:18:59.281 --> 01:19:00.949
all honks and hisses.

1302
01:19:01.992 --> 01:19:03.952
He detests our democracy.

1303
01:19:04.119 --> 01:19:06.663
He fills the pages of his magazine,
America,


1304
01:19:06.830 --> 01:19:09.749
with libelous comments
on all things American.


1305
01:19:09.917 --> 01:19:12.752
Despite a rich wife
and five children,


1306
01:19:12.920 --> 01:19:14.921
he is a compulsive sodomite,

1307
01:19:15.089 --> 01:19:18.091
forever preying on country boys
new to the city.


1308
01:19:19.635 --> 01:19:21.177
It is extreme and...

1309
01:19:22.596 --> 01:19:24.889
He was a good hater, Vidal.

1310
01:19:27.560 --> 01:19:31.354
God knows what is at the very bottom
of that animosity.


1311
01:19:33.482 --> 01:19:35.316
He talked about it every day.

1312
01:19:35.943 --> 01:19:39.612
You don't talk about something
every day that didn't cut you.


1313
01:19:40.030 --> 01:19:42.323
And I don't think
that ever really healed.


1314
01:19:45.077 --> 01:19:48.788
We were in Ravello,
not much to do after dinner.


1315
01:19:49.373 --> 01:19:53.793
He had acquired a VHS copy
of the Vidal/Buckley debates.


1316
01:19:53.961 --> 01:19:56.838
I naively said,
"Do you think we could watch them?"


1317
01:19:57.006 --> 01:20:00.550
Little did I realize this was
the main event for the night.


1318
01:20:02.344 --> 01:20:04.971
We then watched them, I think,
again a couple nights later.


1319
01:20:05.139 --> 01:20:09.350
And on subsequent trips we watched
them two or three times.


1320
01:20:09.518 --> 01:20:12.145
And the thrill
of the first viewing was gone.


1321
01:20:12.313 --> 01:20:14.105
And you began to have the sensation

1322
01:20:14.273 --> 01:20:16.357
that you were edging
into Sunset Boulevard,


1323
01:20:16.525 --> 01:20:18.484
Norma Desmond territory.

1324
01:20:20.112 --> 01:20:22.238
It was Buckley
who was distressed by it.


1325
01:20:24.199 --> 01:20:28.911
Buckley let it become personal
in a way that he had been a maestro


1326
01:20:29.079 --> 01:20:30.330
of being able to avoid.

1327
01:20:30.497 --> 01:20:33.082
And that haunted him
for a very long time.


1328
01:20:36.253 --> 01:20:38.921
After 33 years on PBS,

1329
01:20:39.089 --> 01:20:43.384
William F. Buckley, Jr. taped his
last program before an audience


1330
01:20:43.552 --> 01:20:44.761
of invited guests.

1331
01:20:45.304 --> 01:20:47.805
The last show was succeeded

1332
01:20:47.973 --> 01:20:50.099
by an interview with Ted Koppel.

1333
01:20:50.267 --> 01:20:52.894
And at one point,
he showed


1334
01:20:53.062 --> 01:20:56.481
the now already infamous clip.

1335
01:20:56.649 --> 01:20:59.692
Now listen, you queer,
stop calling me a crypto-Nazi,


1336
01:20:59.985 --> 01:21:04.030
or I'll sock you in the goddamn face
and you'll stay plastered.


1337
01:21:05.658 --> 01:21:08.993
Buckley, uncharacteristically,
said nothing


1338
01:21:09.161 --> 01:21:11.412
and then they went
to the commercial break.


1339
01:21:12.081 --> 01:21:13.790
I was in the audience that day.

1340
01:21:14.208 --> 01:21:19.754
And he made a beeline up the aisle
to where I was sitting and said,


1341
01:21:19.922 --> 01:21:23.216
"I thought that tape
had been destroyed."


1342
01:21:25.010 --> 01:21:28.388
More than 30 years
after the original debates,


1343
01:21:28.555 --> 01:21:31.599
he was still furious with Vidal,

1344
01:21:31.767 --> 01:21:34.519
and still shaken
that he had reacted that way.


1345
01:21:35.479 --> 01:21:38.022
- Do you wish you were 20?
- No!


1346
01:21:38.273 --> 01:21:40.316
Absolutely not.

1347
01:21:41.318 --> 01:21:43.027
No, I would...

1348
01:21:43.195 --> 01:21:46.239
If I had a pill which would
reduce my age by 25 years,


1349
01:21:46.407 --> 01:21:48.157
- I wouldn't take it.
- Why not?


1350
01:21:48.325 --> 01:21:50.910
Because I'm tired of life.

1351
01:21:51.078 --> 01:21:52.829
- Are you really?
- Yeah.


1352
01:21:54.123 --> 01:21:55.123
I really am.

1353
01:21:55.290 --> 01:21:58.918
I'm utterly prepared to stop...

1354
01:21:59.753 --> 01:22:00.878
living on.

1355
01:22:02.089 --> 01:22:05.967
Any regrets about this life
that you have lived?


1356
01:22:08.011 --> 01:22:09.595
- Yeah...
- Like what?


1357
01:22:09.763 --> 01:22:11.681
Well, I'm not sure I'd tell you.

1358
01:22:13.851 --> 01:22:17.311
Someone asked when
Bill Buckley died what Gore thought.


1359
01:22:18.731 --> 01:22:23.276
He said, "I thought that hell
will be a livelier place,


1360
01:22:24.903 --> 01:22:29.073
that he will be permanently
among those he served in life,


1361
01:22:30.617 --> 01:22:34.120
applauding their prejudices
and fanning their hatreds."


1362
01:22:35.956 --> 01:22:37.832
The last line of that piece was:

1363
01:22:38.333 --> 01:22:41.210
"WFB, rest in hell."

1364
01:22:42.755 --> 01:22:44.422
It seems a little farfetched to say

1365
01:22:44.590 --> 01:22:47.508
that Gore Vidal was waiting around
for Buckley to die


1366
01:22:47.676 --> 01:22:49.010
so he could have the last word.

1367
01:22:49.261 --> 01:22:52.847
But I promise you
that he took great pleasure in that.


1368
01:22:54.016 --> 01:22:56.976
He was not satisfied if he didn't
have something to fight against.


1369
01:22:57.144 --> 01:22:58.853
And at the end of his life,
I think he was fighting


1370
01:22:59.021 --> 01:23:01.773
against the ghosts
of all these enemies.


1371
01:23:03.650 --> 01:23:04.942
Truman Capote once famously said,

1372
01:23:05.110 --> 01:23:09.030
that it wasn't a matter of when
Gore Vidal would be forgotten,


1373
01:23:09.198 --> 01:23:11.991
it was more or less
when did he start to be forgotten?


1374
01:23:13.327 --> 01:23:15.787
Gore was convinced this had
happened already.


1375
01:23:16.914 --> 01:23:20.374
The young had forgotten him.
His books weren't being read anymore.


1376
01:23:24.713 --> 01:23:27.924
These figures
become most interesting


1377
01:23:28.091 --> 01:23:30.510
when they're not listened to
so much.


1378
01:23:30.719 --> 01:23:34.055
Because then there's a kind of
big silence inside themselves.


1379
01:23:38.143 --> 01:23:41.979
I compared it in an essay I wrote
to Wallace Stevens' great poem,


1380
01:23:42.481 --> 01:23:45.733
The Snowman, where he says,

1381
01:23:45.901 --> 01:23:47.777
"You have to have
a mind of winter


1382
01:23:47.945 --> 01:23:51.030
to see nothing that is not there

1383
01:23:51.198 --> 01:23:53.157
and the nothing that is."

1384
01:24:05.295 --> 01:24:08.172
I think these great debates
are absolutely nonsense.


1385
01:24:09.341 --> 01:24:12.176
The way they're set up, there's
almost no interchange of ideas,


1386
01:24:12.344 --> 01:24:14.178
very little even of personality.

1387
01:24:14.763 --> 01:24:17.056
There's also a terrible thing
about this medium


1388
01:24:17.224 --> 01:24:18.850
that hardly anyone listens.

1389
01:24:19.434 --> 01:24:21.519
They sort of get an impression
of somebody


1390
01:24:21.687 --> 01:24:23.729
and they think they've figured out
just what he's like


1391
01:24:23.897 --> 01:24:25.606
by seeing him on television.

1392
01:24:26.441 --> 01:24:30.695
The Buckley-Vidal debate
was a harbinger


1393
